<h1 class="post-title">You Were Never Supposed to Invent Your Purpose</h1>
<p class="post-subtitle">The thread was tied before you arrived.</p>
<div class="post-meta">
<span class="post-date">June 10, 2026</span>
<div class="meta-div"></div>
<span class="post-read">11 min read</span>
</div>
</header>
<div class="post-hero">
<img src="images/img-purpose.jpg" alt="You Were Never Supposed to Invent Your Purpose"/>
</div>
<div class="ornament">· · ·</div>
<article>
<p>There is a particular kind of exhaustion that doesn't show up on any medical chart. It's not depression exactly, though it wears depression's coat. It is the specific, bone-deep fatigue of a person who has been asking themselves the same question for years — <em>what is the point of me</em> — and receiving, in return, only silence.</p>
<p>You've tried everything the culture offers. You've made vision boards and written mission statements. You've read the books that told you to follow your passion, find your ikigai, lean into your strengths. And still — underneath it all — a hollow place that nothing quite fills.</p>
<blockquote>You weren't failing at purpose. You were using the wrong map entirely.</blockquote>
<h2>The Philosophy We Absorbed Without Knowing It</h2>
<p>Most of us were handed a set of invisible instructions about meaning through the water we swam in. This worldview has a name and a father: Jean-Paul Sartre. Existentialism. The foundational claim is this: existence precedes essence. You arrive in the world without a predetermined nature, without a built-in purpose. Meaning is something you manufacture through the sheer force of your own will.</p>
<p>But here's what that philosophy quietly does to a person who is already struggling to feel like enough: it turns your entire inner life into a performance review.</p>
<h2>What Viktor Frankl Actually Found</h2>
<p>Viktor Frankl survived four concentration camps, including Auschwitz. And in the extremity of that horror, he made a discovery that existentialism had missed: <em>meaning is not invented. Meaning is found.</em> It arises from something outside the self — from love, from suffering metabolized into service, from the sense that your particular life is woven into something larger than your own story.</p>
<blockquote>You are not where purpose originates. You are where purpose passes through.</blockquote>
<h2>The Red Thread</h2>
<p>In Chinese mythology there is a figure called Yuè Xià Lǎorén — the Old Man Under the Moon. He carries a spool of red thread. Before two people meet — before they are even born — he ties an invisible red cord between them. The cord stretches across any distance. It survives any tangle. It cannot be broken.</p>
<p>What if your connections, your wounds, your obsessions, your particular way of seeing the world — what if none of it was accidental? What if there was a thread running through all of it, leading somewhere?</p>
<p>The existentialist tells you to grab the loom and weave yourself into existence. But the thread was already there. It was always already there. You were never meant to manufacture it. You were meant to follow it.</p>
<h2>What I Want You to Know</h2>
<p>If you have been searching for twenty years — or two, or forty — and you are tired in that particular way, hear this: the search was not wasted. Every dead end was a door closed on a false answer, which is its own kind of grace.</p>
<p>You don't need to invent yourself into significance. You already are significant — not because of what you produce or perform or contribute, but because you are a living node in a web of connection that needed exactly your particular frequency to be complete.</p>
<blockquote>The thread is real. It was tied before you arrived. Your work now is not to manufacture the cord. It is to stop pulling against it — and feel where it leads.</blockquote>
